> Combining the best quality mince with spicy chorizo, the trick to this burger is not to pack
> the meat too tightly and always cook it medium-rare for extra juiciness.

Shred the @baby gem lettuce{1}. Peel and cut the @red onion{1} in half through the root
and then slice it into very thin, half moon shaped slices. Lastly, chop the
@chorizo{1}(diced) really, really finely.

Heat @olive oil{2%tsp} on low heat in a #non-stick pan{}. Add in the red onion with
@?sugar{1/2%tsp} and a @salt{pinch} and @pepper{pinch}. After ~{10%minutes} add half
the @balsamic vinegar{1}(half for onions, half for salad - save the rest for later).
Continue slow cooking until the burgers are ready.

Bring a pan of water to the boil, add in your @corn on the cob{1} and a pinch of salt.
Gently boil the corn for around ~{4%minutes} (more or less depending on how soft you
like it). Drain and keep to the side then pre-heat your #grill{} to high.

For the burgers mix together the @British beef mince{250%g} with @salt{1/4%tsp}. Mix
in the @dried oregano{1%tsp}, the chopped chorizo and the @ketchup{1%tbsp}. Work the
mixture really thoroughly with your hands for a few mins.

Divide the mixture into two portions and gently press each one into a burger shape.
Tip: Try not to compact the meat too much. Rub a light coating of @olive oil{light
coating} on each burger before transferring them to a #baking tray{}. Grill them on
the top shelf nearest the grill for ~{4%minutes} on each side.

In a #bowl{} mix together the baby gem lettuce with @good quality olive oil{2%tsp}
and the remaining balsamic vinegar.

Cut the @brioche bun{2} through the middle so that you have two burger 'baps'. Put
these under the grill for about ~{1%minute} on each side to lightly toast them.

Serve the burgers with the side salad and top with your red onion marmalade.
Chop your corn in half and serve with a @?butter{knob} and a @salt{sprinkle}.

Food of the gods!